794
00:37:37,541 --> 00:37:39,540
- Everything About Tteokbokki.
- Everything About Tteokbokki.

795
00:37:39,541 --> 00:37:40,551
Kim Kwan Hoon.

796
00:37:41,781 --> 00:37:43,951
I wonder how much the tteokbokki is.

797
00:37:44,081 --> 00:37:45,181
- Let's see.
- Let's see.

798
00:37:45,651 --> 00:37:47,320
Tteokbokki, five dollars.

799
00:37:47,321 --> 00:37:50,091
(Ingredient cost: 290.62 dollars)

800
00:37:50,591 --> 00:37:53,491
- Wait, five dollars? Gosh.
- Five dollars?

801
00:37:54,031 --> 00:37:55,161
- My gosh.
- Oh, my.

802
00:37:56,591 --> 00:37:57,601
A clear win.

803
00:37:58,001 --> 00:37:59,401
Amazing. Tteokbokki will get first place.

804
00:37:59,861 --> 00:38:02,771
If the other chefs are providing main menu items,

805
00:38:03,071 --> 00:38:05,040
our team will serve a side menu that can be shared at every table.

806
00:38:05,041 --> 00:38:07,041
Let's become the perfect supporting dish!

807
00:38:07,101 --> 00:38:10,411
Becoming the perfect complementary dish is my strategy.

808
00:38:10,611 --> 00:38:11,910
That's the plan.

809
00:38:11,911 --> 00:38:13,381
(A shareable-menu strategy)

810
00:38:13,611 --> 00:38:14,911
He has to sell 200 dishes.

811
00:38:15,551 --> 00:38:18,281
- But the thing is...
- Serve big portions?

812
00:38:18,551 --> 00:38:20,351
- No. Everyone...
- Yes?

813
00:38:21,221 --> 00:38:22,551
will order it.

814
00:38:23,291 --> 00:38:25,290
- All customers might order it.
- Exactly.

815
00:38:25,291 --> 00:38:28,330
- As a side dish.
- Right?

816
00:38:28,331 --> 00:38:30,061
That's a good idea.

817
00:38:30,701 --> 00:38:33,030
Sell it all out, or just go home.

818
00:38:33,031 --> 00:38:34,331
I've chosen 1 of those 2 options.

819
00:38:42,511 --> 00:38:45,341
The Star In My Heart, Jo Seo Hyung.

820
00:38:46,111 --> 00:38:49,681
(Laughing)

821
00:38:49,751 --> 00:38:51,181
(The Star In My Heart, Jo Seo Hyung)

822
00:38:51,481 --> 00:38:53,550
The chicken with glutinous rice nurungji and Korean calcot.

823
00:38:53,551 --> 00:38:54,551
(Ingredient cost: 404.47 dollars)

824
00:38:54,552 --> 00:38:56,521
It's 28 dollars.

825
00:38:57,561 --> 00:38:59,191
I bet it's the priciest menu.

826
00:39:00,061 --> 00:39:01,291
Twenty-eight dollars?

827
00:39:02,331 --> 00:39:03,390
That's tough.

828
00:39:03,391 --> 00:39:05,431
She's an elimination candidate.

829
00:39:05,561 --> 00:39:06,831
She's standing on a cliff.

830
00:39:07,571 --> 00:39:09,230
The chicken with nurungji and Korean calcot?

831
00:39:09,231 --> 00:39:10,901
In 28 dollars?

832
00:39:12,571 --> 00:39:15,241
It's not a dish you can sell with half-hearted confidence.

833
00:39:15,511 --> 00:39:18,041
- That's an incredible challenge.
- Let's go.

834
00:39:18,841 --> 00:39:19,941
Goodness.

835
00:39:21,951 --> 00:39:23,951
HunGry, Kim Hoon.

836
00:39:24,681 --> 00:39:25,681
Kim Hoon!

837
00:39:25,682 --> 00:39:27,080
(Yongridan-gil Hot Spot Maker Kim Hoon, Teammate Kim Jong In)

838
00:39:27,081 --> 00:39:28,451
We have a pro here.

839
00:39:29,421 --> 00:39:31,291
Tenderloin steak rice.

840
00:39:31,361 --> 00:39:35,030
(Ingredient cost: 572.46 dollars)

841
00:39:35,031 --> 00:39:38,401
(270 dollars over the base ingredient budget)

842
00:39:38,631 --> 00:39:41,330
- As expected.
- Hoon!

843
00:39:41,331 --> 00:39:43,171
(Starting in minus by the amount he overspent)

844
00:39:44,341 --> 00:39:45,540
Nice one.

845
00:39:45,541 --> 00:39:48,110
As expected.

846
00:39:48,111 --> 00:39:49,541
(Everyone is happy for him.)

847
00:39:50,511 --> 00:39:53,111
- Let's do it with spirit!
- We'll sell a lot!

848
00:39:53,441 --> 00:39:54,510
(Kim Hoon, Initial revenue: minus 270 dollars, last place)

849
00:39:54,511 --> 00:39:56,711
- We'll make sure to sell a lot.
- We're going for buzz.

850
00:39:57,251 --> 00:39:59,050
I've already beaten you!

851
00:39:59,051 --> 00:40:00,351
(Go Seok Hyun, Initial revenue: 0 dollars)

852
00:40:01,051 --> 00:40:02,850
- Let's do this.
- I'll see you at dinner.

853
00:40:02,851 --> 00:40:05,820
(Song Hoon, Initial revenue: minus 170 dollars)

854
00:40:05,821 --> 00:40:08,661
If you don't sell out during lunch, you need to do dinner business.

855
00:40:09,331 --> 00:40:10,960
Start preparing...

856
00:40:10,961 --> 00:40:13,661
- for the lunch rush.
- Let's go.

857
00:40:14,701 --> 00:40:17,500
(The 1,000-dollar sales race begins.)

858
00:40:17,501 --> 00:40:18,501
- I'm in your care.
- Good luck.

859
00:40:18,502 --> 00:40:19,571
Please attract many customers.

860
00:40:24,411 --> 00:40:27,951
(5 hours before opening)

861
00:40:31,381 --> 00:40:33,821
First place. We're here to come in first place.

862
00:40:35,121 --> 00:40:36,790
It does feel like foul play...

863
00:40:36,791 --> 00:40:38,460
for Chef Lee Yeon Bok to participate.

864
00:40:38,461 --> 00:40:39,821
He has over 50 years of experience.

865
00:40:40,261 --> 00:40:42,891
His dish gives off that energy, you know?

866
00:40:43,991 --> 00:40:45,631
Chef Lee Yeon Bok. I'm happy to see him,

867
00:40:45,831 --> 00:40:48,131
and yet, I'm quite scared of him.

868
00:40:48,901 --> 00:40:52,071
The 1st team to reach 1,000 dollars in sales is the winner.

869
00:40:52,871 --> 00:40:55,571
What should we sell, and will it work in this market?

870
00:40:56,941 --> 00:40:58,381
In my experience,

871
00:40:58,611 --> 00:41:02,451
business was bad when I sold a dish that came out of nowhere...

872
00:41:02,951 --> 00:41:04,181
and was hard to understand.

873
00:41:04,281 --> 00:41:07,020
Since our customers are office workers,

874
00:41:07,021 --> 00:41:08,391
one menu item should be jjamppong.

875
00:41:09,051 --> 00:41:10,690
Familiar flavors sell.

876
00:41:10,691 --> 00:41:12,691
The dish is easy for anyone to approach.

877
00:41:12,921 --> 00:41:15,491
People know what they're getting.

878
00:41:15,931 --> 00:41:18,000
They already recognize the menu.

879
00:41:18,001 --> 00:41:19,201
(Lee Yeon Bok's strategy: Familiar flavors)

880
00:41:20,331 --> 00:41:21,630
Jjajangmyeon...

881
00:41:21,631 --> 00:41:23,771
is commonly made with pork or shrimp,

882
00:41:23,931 --> 00:41:25,541
but not with freshwater snails.

883
00:41:26,801 --> 00:41:29,571
Freshwater snails have great texture. They're chewy.

884
00:41:29,741 --> 00:41:31,810
Hence, we made freshwater snail jjajangmyeon.

885
00:41:31,811 --> 00:41:32,811
(Menu 1: Freshwater snail jjajangmyeon, 7 dollars)

886
00:41:33,711 --> 00:41:37,621
The jjamppong is topped with well-cooked meat.

887
00:41:38,121 --> 00:41:39,780
Beef loin jjamppong.

888
00:41:39,781 --> 00:41:40,821
(Menu 2: Shrimp and beef loin jjamppong, 12 dollars)

889
00:41:40,851 --> 00:41:43,651
Mianbao xia is our restaurant's signature menu.

890
00:41:44,091 --> 00:41:47,360
It was added to the menu...

891
00:41:47,361 --> 00:41:49,391
to boost sales.

892
00:41:49,591 --> 00:41:51,930
Jjajangmyeon, jjamppong, and mianbao xia.

893
00:41:51,931 --> 00:41:54,570
It's not an exaggeration to say that we're the best at them.

894
00:41:54,571 --> 00:41:56,730
That's why they're our menu items.

895
00:41:56,731 --> 00:41:57,801
(Freshwater snail jjajangmyeon, beef loin and shrimp jjamppong...)

896
00:41:58,871 --> 00:42:01,941
Put your cooking shoes on. We need to get ready.

897
00:42:02,371 --> 00:42:03,770
Let's put them in the freezer first.

898
00:42:03,771 --> 00:42:05,581
- Okay.
- Open the noodles.

899
00:42:08,381 --> 00:42:11,651
As we had a lot to prep in the morning,

900
00:42:12,221 --> 00:42:13,481
- we were in a rush.
- Yes.

901
00:42:13,981 --> 00:42:17,151
(Pressed for time, ripping the packaging open with a knife)

902
00:42:18,161 --> 00:42:20,391
The noodles are still frozen. Interesting.

903
00:42:20,661 --> 00:42:22,361
They were in the freezer.

904
00:42:24,661 --> 00:42:25,661
Oh, dear.

905
00:42:26,131 --> 00:42:27,131
Are you okay?

906
00:42:27,701 --> 00:42:29,430
I was being hasty,

907
00:42:29,431 --> 00:42:32,141
trying to prep quickly.

908
00:42:32,441 --> 00:42:34,740
We should've used scissors or a cutting board and a knife...

909
00:42:34,741 --> 00:42:36,640
to cut the packaging,

910
00:42:36,641 --> 00:42:38,711
but we were on the floor, using a knife while chatting.

911
00:42:38,841 --> 00:42:40,180
That's when I cut my finger.

912
00:42:40,181 --> 00:42:42,810
He asked what was wrong. I told him I cut myself...

913
00:42:42,811 --> 00:42:44,920
and to be careful with his fingers.

914
00:42:44,921 --> 00:42:46,751
Just when we got started.

915
00:42:46,981 --> 00:42:48,391
We're doomed.

916
00:42:52,791 --> 00:42:53,891
Come on.

917
00:42:54,591 --> 00:42:56,631
But he was also in a rush...

918
00:42:56,761 --> 00:42:59,361
- and cut his finger.
- Today will be...

919
00:43:01,401 --> 00:43:02,801
- Back then...
- It was unbelievable.

920
00:43:03,431 --> 00:43:04,871
We're off on a bad start.

921
00:43:05,341 --> 00:43:06,471
In the beginning.

922
00:43:08,441 --> 00:43:09,941
My mind went blank.

923
00:43:10,271 --> 00:43:11,580
"Did this really happen?"

924
00:43:11,581 --> 00:43:13,281
I couldn't believe it.

925
00:43:14,081 --> 00:43:15,781
His cut was bad.

926
00:43:16,381 --> 00:43:18,620
It was a mess. He was bleeding a lot.

927
00:43:18,621 --> 00:43:20,221
We would've just worked if possible.

928
00:43:20,881 --> 00:43:22,191
You should go now.

929
00:43:22,351 --> 00:43:23,951
- Go now.
- You should get it sutured.

930
00:43:24,221 --> 00:43:26,721
The amount of bleeding wasn't something I could put up with.

931
00:43:26,921 --> 00:43:29,291
If things went wrong because of my cut,

932
00:43:29,861 --> 00:43:31,361
I would get us eliminated.

933
00:43:31,961 --> 00:43:33,201
My mind was racing.

934
00:43:34,531 --> 00:43:37,231
I was in full panic mode back then.

935
00:43:38,541 --> 00:43:39,840
(BokBok)

936
00:43:39,841 --> 00:43:43,211
(Lee Yeon Bok is alone in the kitchen.)

937
00:43:44,881 --> 00:43:46,081
I was a bit worried.

938
00:43:46,411 --> 00:43:48,510
I was too busy and swamped.

939
00:43:48,511 --> 00:43:50,850
Other restaurants...

940
00:43:50,851 --> 00:43:52,820
had two people prepping,

941
00:43:52,821 --> 00:43:54,421
but one of us went to the hospital.

942
00:43:54,891 --> 00:43:57,661
I had to prep everything alone.

943
00:44:02,031 --> 00:44:03,491
(BokBok)

944
00:44:05,301 --> 00:44:08,271
Time was ticking. I was really all over the place.

945
00:44:11,241 --> 00:44:12,301
Back then,

946
00:44:13,341 --> 00:44:14,711
I had a small mental breakdown.

947
00:44:25,521 --> 00:44:27,151
Today is going to be chaotic.

948
00:44:29,191 --> 00:44:32,891
(Leaving Yeon Bok, who is struggling alone)

949
00:44:33,661 --> 00:44:37,231
(Another store with 3 Chinese wok ranges)

950
00:44:37,431 --> 00:44:39,331
(Sunlin)

951
00:44:39,661 --> 00:44:43,471
(A Chinese-style orange-colored exterior and signboard)

952
00:44:54,351 --> 00:44:56,011
Dad, I'm leaving this here.

953
00:44:56,251 --> 00:44:58,151
Yes, okay.

954
00:45:02,851 --> 00:45:06,661
(Top 4 Legendary Chinese Chef, Yoo Bang Nyeong of Sunlin)

955
00:45:08,531 --> 00:45:11,231
I personally know Lee Yeon Bok.

956
00:45:12,861 --> 00:45:15,131
We worked together when we were young.

957
00:45:16,071 --> 00:45:18,271
Was it 1978 or 1979?

958
00:45:18,641 --> 00:45:20,441
We worked together at the same hotel.

959
00:45:21,211 --> 00:45:22,411
I was in my 20s...

960
00:45:22,941 --> 00:45:24,211
when I went to clubs every night.

961
00:45:26,141 --> 00:45:29,351
I can't talk about it. Even my wife doesn't know about it.

962
00:45:30,111 --> 00:45:31,981
Who's that? Isn't it Yoo Bang Nyeong?

963
00:45:32,281 --> 00:45:33,381
Yes, hi.

964
00:45:33,821 --> 00:45:34,921
Hey, friend.

965
00:45:35,891 --> 00:45:38,221
We met again after 20 to 30 years.

966
00:45:38,721 --> 00:45:41,730
We were coworkers back then. Now, we're competing with each other.

967
00:45:41,731 --> 00:45:42,961
We're rivals.

968
00:45:43,091 --> 00:45:45,701
When the time comes, you might see blood.

969
00:45:47,971 --> 00:45:50,401
They'll scan the booths...

970
00:45:50,831 --> 00:45:53,570
- and then decide on mine.
- You'll succeed no matter where.

971
00:45:53,571 --> 00:45:55,211
The spot that...

972
00:45:55,471 --> 00:45:58,141
Lee Yeon Bok chose was the one I had in mind.

973
00:45:59,041 --> 00:46:01,411
Yoo Bang Nyeong needs to stay away since we both cook Chinese.

974
00:46:04,481 --> 00:46:05,481
(Lee Yeon Bok)

975
00:46:05,482 --> 00:46:07,751
- I was going to put mine here.
- Next to mine?

976
00:46:09,221 --> 00:46:11,161
- Kind of like Chinatown.
- Chinatown?

977
00:46:11,291 --> 00:46:12,420
- Chinatown?
- Chinatown.

978
00:46:12,421 --> 00:46:13,421
Chinatown.

979
00:46:13,422 --> 00:46:16,361
Lee Yeon Bok took that spot.

980
00:46:17,361 --> 00:46:18,601
Yoo Bang Nyeong,

981
00:46:19,461 --> 00:46:21,101
choose your slot.

982
00:46:21,271 --> 00:46:22,471
I'm going over there.

983
00:46:22,971 --> 00:46:25,801
On the opposite side of Chef Yeon Bok.

984
00:46:26,901 --> 00:46:28,941
- They're facing each other.
- Interesting.

985
00:46:29,571 --> 00:46:30,611
Nice.

986
00:46:33,711 --> 00:46:34,751
Head-to-head.

987
00:46:35,781 --> 00:46:36,911
Chinese Cuisine Master.

988
00:46:37,211 --> 00:46:40,020
- My gosh.
- Oh, my.

989
00:46:40,021 --> 00:46:41,321
A battle between the two.

990
00:46:41,421 --> 00:46:44,590
I chose the spot right across from Lee Yeon Bok's.

991
00:46:44,591 --> 00:46:45,891
(Yoo Bang Nyeong, Lee Yeon Bok)

992
00:46:48,461 --> 00:46:51,531
(BokBok)

993
00:46:52,831 --> 00:46:53,831
Sunlin.

994
00:46:53,832 --> 00:46:55,030
(Sunlin)

995
00:46:55,031 --> 00:46:56,371
It's right across from us.

996
00:46:57,531 --> 00:47:00,441
What dishes was Lee Yeon Bok selling again?

997
00:47:01,041 --> 00:47:02,441
- Mianbao xia.
- Right.

998
00:47:03,041 --> 00:47:04,811
Beef brisket jjamppong.

999
00:47:05,041 --> 00:47:06,140
Beef brisket jjamppong?

1000
00:47:06,141 --> 00:47:07,240
(BokBok prepared classic Chinese dishes.)

1001
00:47:07,241 --> 00:47:09,610
I was worried Yoo Bang Nyeong's menu...

1002
00:47:09,611 --> 00:47:12,451
would overlap with ours.

1003
00:47:12,951 --> 00:47:14,450
Yoo Bang Nyeong is the only other chef...

1004
00:47:14,451 --> 00:47:15,890
serving traditional Chinese cuisine like us.

1005
00:47:15,891 --> 00:47:17,451
(Sunlin)

1006
00:47:17,551 --> 00:47:20,061
They're getting on our nerves the most.

1007
00:47:21,591 --> 00:47:23,891
I wonder what Yoo Bang Nyeong will serve.

1008
00:47:26,661 --> 00:47:30,001
The customers are office workers. Lunch should be tasty...

1009
00:47:30,301 --> 00:47:31,671
while being cheap.

1010
00:47:32,641 --> 00:47:34,301
What's more, it shouldn't take long.

1011
00:47:37,071 --> 00:47:38,111
Jjajangmyeon.

1012
00:47:39,011 --> 00:47:40,081
I...

1013
00:47:40,781 --> 00:47:42,550
have been cooking jjajang...

1014
00:47:42,551 --> 00:47:44,521
since the moment I learned how to use a wok.

1015
00:47:46,321 --> 00:47:49,791
The number of jjajangmyeon dishes I have made is countless.

1016
00:47:56,691 --> 00:47:58,701
I can tell if it's bland or salty...

1017
00:47:59,131 --> 00:48:00,601
just by its smell.

1018
00:48:07,271 --> 00:48:08,271
Okay.

1019
00:48:08,711 --> 00:48:11,710
(He cooked jjajang in no time.)

1020
00:48:11,711 --> 00:48:13,040
Fill it with cold water.

1021
00:48:13,041 --> 00:48:15,511
(Yoo Bang Nyeong)

1022
00:48:16,351 --> 00:48:17,650
(Bang Nyeong is cooling down the freshly made jjajang.)

1023
00:48:17,651 --> 00:48:19,451
Put in some ice.

1024
00:48:22,721 --> 00:48:25,561
Every jjajangmyeon dish can have its own unique taste.

1025
00:48:27,061 --> 00:48:28,630
(Sunlin)

1026
00:48:28,631 --> 00:48:29,890
Five-color bibim jjajang.

1027
00:48:29,891 --> 00:48:31,601
(Five-color bibim jjajang, 9.50 dollars)

1028
00:48:31,761 --> 00:48:34,161
I may be old, but I'm trying to stay young.

1029
00:48:35,131 --> 00:48:38,801
Cooking also changes with time.

1030
00:48:39,141 --> 00:48:43,041
You hit a wall if you only cook plain jjajangmyeon every day.

1031
00:48:43,271 --> 00:48:45,940
You must come up with new dishes.

1032
00:48:45,941 --> 00:48:46,981
Okay.

1033
00:48:47,541 --> 00:48:49,410
Our jjajang is enjoyed cold.

1034
00:48:49,411 --> 00:48:50,811
(Cooling the jjajang sauce for about 2 hours)

1035
00:48:52,551 --> 00:48:54,821
(The freshly cooked noodles are immediately rinsed in cold water.)

1036
00:48:55,421 --> 00:48:58,691
(Topping it off with some jjajang sauce)

1037
00:49:00,221 --> 00:49:04,160
The garnishes are in four colors. With the color of the jjajang,

1038
00:49:04,161 --> 00:49:06,030
it has five colors in total.

1039
00:49:06,031 --> 00:49:07,360
(5 colors complete with 4 garnishes and jjajang)

1040
00:49:07,361 --> 00:49:10,270
Pickled onion gives it that tanginess.

1041
00:49:10,271 --> 00:49:14,171
Together with the jjajang sauce, it creates a novel taste.

1042
00:49:14,671 --> 00:49:16,341
I do feel the pressure.

1043
00:49:16,611 --> 00:49:19,411
But trying something new is necessary.

1044
00:49:19,911 --> 00:49:21,241
Only then will the customers think,

1045
00:49:21,551 --> 00:49:24,750
"This jjajangmyeon is different from the one..."

1046
00:49:24,751 --> 00:49:27,221
"at Yoo Bang Nyeong's Chinatown restaurant."

1047
00:49:27,881 --> 00:49:29,751
With a new brand,

1048
00:49:29,851 --> 00:49:31,991
we can introduce a new dish.

1049
00:49:35,461 --> 00:49:36,860
It's a type of mianbao xia.

1050
00:49:36,861 --> 00:49:37,930
(Shrimp mix)

1051
00:49:37,931 --> 00:49:39,501
I made it with Chinese twisted donuts.

1052
00:49:43,431 --> 00:49:44,670
Youtiao xia.

1053
00:49:44,671 --> 00:49:46,441
(Youtiao xia, a new type of mianbao xia)

1054
00:49:46,571 --> 00:49:48,041
They are yellow jalapenos.

1055
00:49:48,711 --> 00:49:50,871
I haven't seen a Chinese restaurant in Korea use one.

1056
00:49:52,181 --> 00:49:55,911
Yellow jalapeno peppers are spicier and tastier than normal ones.

1057
00:49:56,381 --> 00:49:57,650
(Yellow chili meat rice bowl, a new type of beef rice bowl)

1058
00:49:57,651 --> 00:49:58,780
Beef rice bowl.

1059
00:49:58,781 --> 00:50:00,181
(Yellow chili meat rice bowl, a new type of beef rice bowl)

1060
00:50:03,021 --> 00:50:04,091
Oh, my gosh.

1061
00:50:06,121 --> 00:50:08,191
I've lost.

1062
00:50:09,961 --> 00:50:11,801
How much will it appeal to customers?

1063
00:50:12,461 --> 00:50:14,360
It's a challenge.

1064
00:50:14,361 --> 00:50:16,171
(BokBok)

1065
00:50:16,371 --> 00:50:17,930
(Sunlin)

1066
00:50:17,931 --> 00:50:19,400
A part of me is filled with worries.

1067
00:50:19,401 --> 00:50:22,471
But you never know what'll happen until it actually does.

1068
00:50:22,671 --> 00:50:23,810
(A Chinese cuisine showdown across the street)

1069
00:50:23,811 --> 00:50:26,011
Is BokBok's jjajangmyeon better than ours?

1070
00:50:26,711 --> 00:50:29,111
That's for the customer to judge.

1071
00:50:32,381 --> 00:50:34,991
A flavor you've never tasted before.

1072
00:50:35,491 --> 00:50:36,651
The stove works.

1073
00:50:37,691 --> 00:50:40,421
I want the customers to look forward to that.

1074
00:50:41,631 --> 00:50:42,660
Next...

1075
00:50:42,661 --> 00:50:45,961
The chefs who could possibly have a tough time are...

1076
00:50:46,001 --> 00:50:47,900
those in fine dining.

1077
00:50:47,901 --> 00:50:49,901
I don't think Chef Lim Ki Hak will win.

1078
00:50:50,101 --> 00:50:51,600
Those who actually do business...

1079
00:50:51,601 --> 00:50:53,241
should win this survival show.

1080
00:50:53,471 --> 00:50:56,071
We're technically in a battlefield.

1081
00:50:57,871 --> 00:50:59,881
A sense of crisis? None.

1082
00:51:03,111 --> 00:51:04,351
No matter how much I thought about it,

1083
00:51:05,151 --> 00:51:07,021
it came across as interesting.

1084
00:51:07,121 --> 00:51:08,621
Something that lived only in my imagination.

1085
00:51:08,791 --> 00:51:11,491
"Will the customers come to like this?"

1086
00:51:12,021 --> 00:51:14,891
It's something worth trying.

1087
00:51:15,761 --> 00:51:18,761
First off, our theme should be...

1088
00:51:19,401 --> 00:51:22,900
French cuisine, no question asked. But a more approachable one.

1089
00:51:22,901 --> 00:51:24,900
(The popularization of French cuisine)

1090
00:51:24,901 --> 00:51:26,541
If there's one thing that's different,

1091
00:51:26,641 --> 00:51:28,610
it's that we won't change...

1092
00:51:28,611 --> 00:51:31,940
our concept even if we get a mission.

1093
00:51:31,941 --> 00:51:33,711
Regardless of the kind of mission,

1094
00:51:33,881 --> 00:51:37,411
we plan to serve French cuisine on a single plate.

1095
00:51:38,151 --> 00:51:39,851
The name is Bol A Bol.

1096
00:51:40,081 --> 00:51:41,181
One plate.

1097
00:51:41,891 --> 00:51:43,451
The dish we prepared...

1098
00:51:44,091 --> 00:51:46,490
is a simple lunch...

1099
00:51:46,491 --> 00:51:50,131
featuring a condensed three-course French meal.

1100
00:51:51,161 --> 00:51:52,531
Poulet basquaise.

1101
00:51:53,331 --> 00:51:57,201
In Korean, it would be spicy stir-fried chicken rice bowl.

1102
00:51:57,371 --> 00:51:59,840
If the meat is served over rice in a bowl,

1103
00:51:59,841 --> 00:52:01,511
it could easily appeal to the public.

1104
00:52:01,771 --> 00:52:04,370
I also wanted to serve some sausages.

1105
00:52:04,371 --> 00:52:07,481
Rice with sausages on top. It's hearty, isn't it?

1106
00:52:08,181 --> 00:52:11,051
I handmade the sausages.

1107
00:52:11,651 --> 00:52:14,320
There's also dessert. Creme caramel.

1108
00:52:14,321 --> 00:52:15,821
(Creme caramel, 4.50 dollars)

1109
00:52:16,091 --> 00:52:20,221
We practiced the same dishes twice.

1110
00:52:20,821 --> 00:52:22,261
I was confident.

1111
00:52:26,031 --> 00:52:29,131
I will start cooking the poulet basquaise.

1112
00:52:30,871 --> 00:52:35,270
Searing the chicken well on high heat...

1113
00:52:35,271 --> 00:52:37,341
was the most important first task.

1114
00:52:38,381 --> 00:52:39,841
Chicken drumsticks.

1115
00:52:47,351 --> 00:52:48,451
I was in full concentration mode...

1116
00:52:49,021 --> 00:52:50,921
to cook the chicken well.

1117
00:52:53,291 --> 00:52:55,960
How well the chicken sears...

1118
00:52:55,961 --> 00:52:59,101
accounts for half of how good the dish will taste.

1119
00:53:04,231 --> 00:53:07,401
(Stir-frying onions in the leftover chicken fat)

1120
00:53:13,281 --> 00:53:15,481
As stir-frying the onions,

1121
00:53:15,781 --> 00:53:19,751
I started to see the next steps.

1122
00:53:26,921 --> 00:53:30,390
Where is our canned tomato?

1123
00:53:30,391 --> 00:53:31,931
- What did you say? Can?
- Canned tomato.

1124
00:53:35,631 --> 00:53:36,701
Canned tomato...

1125
00:53:36,971 --> 00:53:38,171
This is bad.

1126
00:53:39,371 --> 00:53:40,601
Canned tomato...

1127
00:53:41,371 --> 00:53:43,041
Gosh, this is serious.

1128
00:53:43,071 --> 00:53:45,741
I was the one in charge of packing the ingredients.

1129
00:53:46,311 --> 00:53:48,680
The moment I heard the word "tomato,"

1130
00:53:48,681 --> 00:53:50,181
I realized I forgot to pack it.

1131
00:53:52,481 --> 00:53:55,220
Tomatoes are one of the core ingredients...

1132
00:53:55,221 --> 00:53:56,351
for poulet basquaise.

1133
00:53:58,361 --> 00:53:59,761
This is an absolute emergency.

1134
00:54:01,221 --> 00:54:03,660
I couldn't find it anywhere. I saw the can opener, but...

1135
00:54:03,661 --> 00:54:04,961
Why did we even bring the can opener?

1136
00:54:07,931 --> 00:54:10,531
What should I do if there are no tomatoes?

1137
00:54:11,841 --> 00:54:14,341
But I couldn't just stop there.

1138
00:54:14,601 --> 00:54:16,111
The show must go on.

1139
00:54:18,681 --> 00:54:19,781
Will they have it at the grocery store?

1140
00:54:20,081 --> 00:54:21,341
I don't know. I'll go check.

1141
00:54:22,981 --> 00:54:24,410
I'll go to the grocery store now.

1142
00:54:24,411 --> 00:54:26,050
- I'm done with this. I'll go now.
- Okay.

1143
00:54:26,051 --> 00:54:27,281
Make it quick.

1144
00:54:27,481 --> 00:54:28,691
I'll be right back.

1145
00:54:28,951 --> 00:54:31,051
I'll buy anything that's related to tomatoes.

1146
00:54:36,061 --> 00:54:38,861
(Grocery store)

1147
00:54:39,131 --> 00:54:40,830
(The cost of additional ingredients is deducted...)

1148
00:54:40,831 --> 00:54:42,501
(from the revenue at retail price.)

1149
00:54:43,731 --> 00:54:44,941
Please.

1150
00:54:45,601 --> 00:54:47,401
I have a bad feeling that they don't have it.

1151
00:54:50,271 --> 00:54:52,310
Since I couldn't move on to the next step,

1152
00:54:52,311 --> 00:54:53,481
I turned off the stove.

1153
00:54:54,311 --> 00:54:57,951
It wasn't a situation where I could blame anyone.

1154
00:54:58,111 --> 00:55:00,421
It was a situation where I just had to find a solution.

1155
00:55:02,491 --> 00:55:04,691
Do you have tomatoes here? Oh, there.

1156
00:55:05,121 --> 00:55:07,761
(He found fresh tomatoes.)

1157
00:55:09,731 --> 00:55:13,501
(45 tomatoes: 36 dollars)

1158
00:55:14,031 --> 00:55:16,071
- Please wait. I'll be right back.
- Okay.

1159
00:55:18,301 --> 00:55:20,841
Chef, they only have ripe tomatoes.

1160
00:55:21,471 --> 00:55:23,841
There are 45 of them.

1161
00:55:24,511 --> 00:55:26,911
- Price?
- It's over 30 dollars.

1162
00:55:27,041 --> 00:55:28,451
- Ripe tomatoes?
- Yes.

1163
00:55:32,851 --> 00:55:35,120
Buy all the tomatoes there.

1164
00:55:35,121 --> 00:55:36,151
Okay.

1165
00:55:36,791 --> 00:55:38,191
I'll buy all of these.

1166
00:55:38,461 --> 00:55:40,021
Yes. I'll have these.

1167
00:55:40,561 --> 00:55:42,030
- All of them?
- How do I pay?

1168
00:55:42,031 --> 00:55:43,290
It will be deducted from the revenue later.

1169
00:55:43,291 --> 00:55:44,530
Okay. I get it.

1170
00:55:44,531 --> 00:55:46,861
(The initial revenue of Bol A Bol: minus 77.87 dollars)

1171
00:55:47,461 --> 00:55:49,801
(Returning with a box of tomatoes)

1172
00:55:50,201 --> 00:55:52,370
- How many do we have?
- There are 45 tomatoes.

1173
00:55:52,371 --> 00:55:53,571
- We have 45 tomatoes?
- Yes.

1174
00:55:53,741 --> 00:55:55,011
Hoon, slice them first.

1175
00:55:55,141 --> 00:55:56,141
- These?
- Yes.

1176
00:55:56,141 --> 00:55:57,141
Okay. I'll slice them first.

1177
00:55:59,641 --> 00:56:01,541
I'm not sure if we can get the right flavor with these.

1178
00:56:03,581 --> 00:56:05,181
The amount is about right, but...

1179
00:56:05,451 --> 00:56:07,021
I think the taste will be completely different.

1180
00:56:07,621 --> 00:56:10,750
The richness and sweetness...

1181
00:56:10,751 --> 00:56:13,490
of Italian tomatoes and domestic tomatoes...

1182
00:56:13,491 --> 00:56:14,721
are completely different.

1183
00:56:15,761 --> 00:56:19,201
I worried a lot about how to bring out a rich flavor...

1184
00:56:20,331 --> 00:56:23,731
when the core ingredients were missing.

1185
00:56:33,081 --> 00:56:35,010
(Thinking)

1186
00:56:35,011 --> 00:56:37,010
- We can make it work.
- Okay.

1187
00:56:37,011 --> 00:56:38,311
- We can do this.
- Yes.

1188
00:56:39,521 --> 00:56:42,051
Then, what we need right now is...

1189
00:56:43,121 --> 00:56:44,921
What we need now is...

1190
00:56:46,491 --> 00:56:47,621
Chicken powder.

1191
00:56:48,661 --> 00:56:50,491
An ingredient I have never used before.

1192
00:56:53,001 --> 00:56:56,871
Just in case the flavor doesn't come through properly,

1193
00:56:57,001 --> 00:56:59,971
I did prepare those seasonings as a backup.

1194
00:57:00,301 --> 00:57:01,871
Should we add a bit of a familiar taste?

1195
00:57:03,041 --> 00:57:05,381
(Picking up pure black pepper)

1196
00:57:05,541 --> 00:57:08,850
(Familiar taste)

1197
00:57:08,851 --> 00:57:11,111
I can't believe I'm even using pure black pepper.

1198
00:57:12,581 --> 00:57:15,421
This is my first time using pure black pepper on my own dish.

1199
00:57:16,051 --> 00:57:17,350
I'm adding 30g of doubanjiang.

1200
00:57:17,351 --> 00:57:19,361
(Doubanjiang with a spicy umami flavor)

1201
00:57:20,791 --> 00:57:23,491
Did we add Cheongyang chili peppers in the middle of it?

1202
00:57:23,991 --> 00:57:25,461
We have to bring out the flavor from here somehow.

1203
00:57:26,501 --> 00:57:29,600
We used a lot of spices...

1204
00:57:29,601 --> 00:57:30,700
that are familiar to Koreans...

1205
00:57:30,701 --> 00:57:32,771
and even chili peppers.

1206
00:57:34,741 --> 00:57:36,141
I'm so worried about how it will taste.

1207
00:57:37,241 --> 00:57:39,011
I'll taste it.

1208
00:57:44,151 --> 00:57:45,281
It's good.

1209
00:57:48,121 --> 00:57:51,121
The flavor actually turned out much better than I expected.

1210
00:57:52,291 --> 00:57:54,991
I think using the doubanjiang was a stroke of genius.

1211
00:57:56,931 --> 00:57:58,431
How much were the tomatoes?

1212
00:57:58,631 --> 00:58:00,501
- They were 36 dollars.
- Great.

1213
00:58:01,361 --> 00:58:02,831
We just need to sell two more servings.

1214
00:58:03,071 --> 00:58:04,131
Okay.

1215
00:58:04,771 --> 00:58:07,440
I'm sorry that I forgot to bring them.

1216
00:58:07,441 --> 00:58:08,641
Don't be.

1217
00:58:08,711 --> 00:58:11,810
I'm just afraid we won't get the result we wanted.

1218
00:58:11,811 --> 00:58:13,041
- That's not true.
- Okay.

1219
00:58:13,181 --> 00:58:14,911
I didn't double-check either.

1220
00:58:16,451 --> 00:58:18,351
We can't say it's entirely your fault.

1221
00:58:19,221 --> 00:58:20,250
I was afraid...

1222
00:58:20,251 --> 00:58:22,221
Hoon would think it was his fault that he forgot it.

1223
00:58:22,721 --> 00:58:25,291
I just wanted to make sure...

1224
00:58:25,791 --> 00:58:27,961
he wouldn't feel that way after it happened.

1225
00:58:29,161 --> 00:58:30,991
Everything is perfect, except for the canned tomatoes.

1226
00:58:32,231 --> 00:58:34,361
No. They say every cloud has a silver lining. It's okay.

1227
00:58:36,101 --> 00:58:37,571
- No problem.
- Okay.

1228
00:58:39,141 --> 00:58:40,240
(Min's)

1229
00:58:40,241 --> 00:58:41,441
This is the problem.

1230
00:58:43,211 --> 00:58:45,110
- This isn't working.
- It will work. It's working.

1231
00:58:45,111 --> 00:58:47,110
- No, it's not.
- I'm sure it will work.

1232
00:58:47,111 --> 00:58:48,181
(Kim Min Seong, the husband, Park Min, the wife)

1233
00:58:48,381 --> 00:58:50,380
No, Min Seong. It's not working.

1234
00:58:50,381 --> 00:58:51,750
(A team with a lot of bickering)

1235
00:58:51,751 --> 00:58:52,881
You always say that.

1236
00:58:53,451 --> 00:58:55,891
I run a Japanese restaurant called Kuma in Yeouido.

1237
00:58:56,021 --> 00:58:57,720
My name is Kim Min Seong. Nice to meet you.

1238
00:58:57,721 --> 00:58:58,891
(Yeouido Sashimi Chairman, Kim Min Seong)

1239
00:58:59,261 --> 00:59:02,031
I've been cooking for about 30 years now.

1240
00:59:02,391 --> 00:59:06,131
And I've been a fixture in Yeouido for the past 20 years.

1241
00:59:07,001 --> 00:59:09,070
Our restaurant is a place where you can find a list of fish...

1242
00:59:09,071 --> 00:59:10,371
that people are curious about.

1243
00:59:11,941 --> 00:59:13,470
Such as 100kg jewfish,

1244
00:59:13,471 --> 00:59:15,371
200kg or 300kg tuna,

1245
00:59:17,511 --> 00:59:19,081
giant grouper over 20kg,

1246
00:59:19,411 --> 00:59:21,441
large sharks, and so on.

1247
00:59:21,681 --> 00:59:24,611
We handle fish that ordinary seafood restaurants can't.

1248
00:59:25,921 --> 00:59:27,450
Our restaurant is practically an all-you-can-eat place.

1249
00:59:27,451 --> 00:59:29,321
If customers ask for more, we give them as much as they want.

1250
00:59:29,751 --> 00:59:32,690
Since Kuma has the concept where they serve...

1251
00:59:32,691 --> 00:59:34,121
extremely high-quality fish...

1252
00:59:35,121 --> 00:59:37,030
I'm sorry to say this,

1253
00:59:37,031 --> 00:59:38,601
but it doesn't seem like they're trying to make money.

1254
00:59:39,261 --> 00:59:41,661
I wonder if they can even make...

1255
00:59:42,071 --> 00:59:44,831
any profit by selling it at that price.

1256
00:59:46,941 --> 00:59:49,870
It says "Yeouido Sashimi Chairman."

1257
00:59:49,871 --> 00:59:53,611
(The self-proclaimed and publicly recognized sashimi expert)

1258
00:59:53,811 --> 00:59:57,151
You're given 300 dollars for the ingredients.

1259
00:59:59,051 --> 01:00:00,521
A budget of 300 dollars?

1260
01:00:01,751 --> 01:00:03,650
Are you going to serve sashimi?

1261
01:00:03,651 --> 01:00:05,861
No. We don't have any good fish for sashimi in March.

1262
01:00:06,161 --> 01:00:07,260
There's only spring ridged-eye flounder.

1263
01:00:07,261 --> 01:00:09,090
Other than that, there aren't many types of fish available.

1264
01:00:09,091 --> 01:00:11,460
And we can't stay within budget with just 300 dollars.

1265
01:00:11,461 --> 01:00:12,461
I see.

1266
01:00:12,461 --> 01:00:13,461
There's no way we can serve sashimi.

1267
01:00:17,031 --> 01:00:18,300
A 300 dollar ingredient budget is way too low.

1268
01:00:18,301 --> 01:00:21,371
Our food costs have always exceeded 40 to 50 percent of the prime cost.

1269
01:00:22,141 --> 01:00:26,381
People call my husband a man obsessed with ingredients.

1270
01:00:26,511 --> 01:00:28,511
He's someone who handles high-quality ingredients...

1271
01:00:28,541 --> 01:00:30,851
without even thinking about the price.

1272
01:00:33,521 --> 01:00:35,950
With only 300 dollars, I can't think of any sashimi menu...

1273
01:00:35,951 --> 01:00:36,951
that I can serve.

1274
01:00:38,321 --> 01:00:42,261
("Sashimi Chairman" can't serve "sashimi" here.)

1275
01:00:43,061 --> 01:00:45,301
(What is the alternative menu of the sashimi expert?)

1276
01:00:47,131 --> 01:00:49,131
This is the highest-grade Korean beef.

1277
01:00:51,771 --> 01:00:52,970
(Top secret curry)

1278
01:00:52,971 --> 01:00:54,201
I'll start making curry then.

1279
01:00:55,201 --> 01:00:56,541
There's something called Korean beef scrapes.

1280
01:00:56,941 --> 01:00:58,810
It's meat cut off from different parts.

1281
01:00:58,811 --> 01:01:00,240
(Leftover meat trimmed from various cuts during butchering)

1282
01:01:00,241 --> 01:01:02,810
Because the shapes are irregular, it's on the cheaper side.

1283
01:01:02,811 --> 01:01:05,151
Still, they are the highest grade, so the quality is excellent.

1284
01:01:05,751 --> 01:01:08,320
It's a curry made by boiling beef and vegetables thoroughly...

1285
01:01:08,321 --> 01:01:10,251
in a pressure cooker, and then blending them together.

1286
01:01:11,491 --> 01:01:13,861
Even if we give it out generously, we can have over 100 servings.

1287
01:01:14,191 --> 01:01:15,390
(100 servings of the top secret curry are done.)

1288
01:01:15,391 --> 01:01:16,661
It's better to have too much than not enough.

1289
01:01:22,101 --> 01:01:24,131
(A hot spring egg)

1290
01:01:24,771 --> 01:01:26,240
It has to taste good.

1291
01:01:26,241 --> 01:01:27,340
(Top secret curry, 12 dollars)

1292
01:01:27,341 --> 01:01:28,741
It has to taste good.

1293
01:01:29,811 --> 01:01:31,210
But how did everyone else...

1294
01:01:31,211 --> 01:01:33,041
buy all their ingredients within 300 dollars?

1295
01:01:33,481 --> 01:01:35,081
The one I understand the least is the raw fish guksu.

1296
01:01:36,611 --> 01:01:38,081
Will they be able to manage the cost?

1297
01:01:38,481 --> 01:01:40,020
How much is the price? Is it 15 dollars?

1298
01:01:40,021 --> 01:01:41,181
I guess it's 13 dollars.

1299
01:01:41,421 --> 01:01:42,520
Is it 13 dollars?

1300
01:01:42,521 --> 01:01:43,590
I could never sell it at that price.

1301
01:01:43,591 --> 01:01:45,221
I can't even source raw fish at that price.

1302
01:01:46,321 --> 01:01:47,561
It's impossible.

1303
01:01:49,291 --> 01:01:51,130
(Gotgan)

1304
01:01:51,131 --> 01:01:54,231
(Jeju raw fish guksu set)

1305
01:01:57,931 --> 01:01:59,001
Hello.

1306
01:01:59,141 --> 01:02:01,970
I run a noodle place in Gyeongdong Market.

1307
01:02:01,971 --> 01:02:03,811
I also run Jeulgeoun Soolsang in Chang-dong...

1308
01:02:04,171 --> 01:02:07,180
and Bada Soolsang on Jeju Island.

1309
01:02:07,181 --> 01:02:08,310
My name is Kim Mi Ryeong.

1310
01:02:08,311 --> 01:02:10,381
(Kim Mi Ryeong with 30 years of experience in Korean cuisine)

1311
01:02:10,611 --> 01:02:13,250
It's sold at a traditional market, so the price is cheap.

1312
01:02:13,251 --> 01:02:15,950
A bowl of noodles is only 10 dollars,

1313
01:02:15,951 --> 01:02:19,120
but I pulled up our monthly sales to 150,000 dollars.

1314
01:02:19,121 --> 01:02:21,691
It's not easy. It's a low-margin, high-volume business.

1315
01:02:22,231 --> 01:02:24,290
This isn't a cooking survival show, after all.

1316
01:02:24,291 --> 01:02:25,960
This is a business survival show.

1317
01:02:25,961 --> 01:02:28,261
I have total confidence when it comes to business.

1318
01:02:28,701 --> 01:02:30,501
I can make and serve food right away,

1319
01:02:30,671 --> 01:02:34,101
keep up the speed, and handle a large number of customers at once.

1320
01:02:35,341 --> 01:02:37,340
I believe that's my strength.

1321
01:02:37,341 --> 01:02:39,141
(30 years proven in the market)

1322
01:02:40,081 --> 01:02:41,111
Turn down the heat just a little.

1323
01:02:42,281 --> 01:02:43,751
Am I your assistant or something?

1324
01:02:44,381 --> 01:02:45,651
I gave birth to him.

1325
01:02:46,521 --> 01:02:48,180
I created him.

1326
01:02:48,181 --> 01:02:49,350
She did.

1327
01:02:49,351 --> 01:02:50,721
(Her teammate and her son, Lee Jun Seong)

1328
01:02:50,891 --> 01:02:53,260
Since elementary school, he's come to the kitchen...

1329
01:02:53,261 --> 01:02:54,420
to wash dishes, pick up trash, and serve food.

1330
01:02:54,421 --> 01:02:55,630
He is highly experienced.

1331
01:02:55,631 --> 01:02:57,760
He's young in age, but heavy on experience.

1332
01:02:57,761 --> 01:03:00,001
So, I think we will have great chemistry.

1333
01:03:01,901 --> 01:03:04,671
(The raw fish in question)

1334
01:03:12,541 --> 01:03:14,011
We're going to serve raw fish guksu.

1335
01:03:15,711 --> 01:03:18,051
We predicted that...

1336
01:03:18,251 --> 01:03:21,051
no one would be serving raw fish here.

1337
01:03:21,581 --> 01:03:23,050
(Jeju raw fish guksu set, Ingredient cost: 249.23 dollars)

1338
01:03:23,051 --> 01:03:24,321
- Unbelievable.
- For raw fish?

1339
01:03:24,821 --> 01:03:28,261
What kind of fish did they use to only spend 249 dollars?

1340
01:03:28,561 --> 01:03:30,631
What kind of fish did they use?

1341
01:03:31,161 --> 01:03:32,801
What kind of fish do they serve?

1342
01:03:33,761 --> 01:03:35,631
No matter how much I thought, I couldn't figure it out.

1343
01:03:36,601 --> 01:03:37,900
- What are they using?
- What is it?

1344
01:03:37,901 --> 01:03:39,101
(Everyone was curious about the raw fish.)

1345
01:03:39,271 --> 01:03:40,600
There are specific types of fish for this.

1346
01:03:40,601 --> 01:03:43,111
We can't make raw fish guksu with red seabream.

1347
01:03:43,641 --> 01:03:45,941
- Yellowtail amberjack is in season.
- It's called yellowtail amberjack.

1348
01:03:46,181 --> 01:03:47,481
The price is very cheap.

1349
01:03:48,851 --> 01:03:50,180
We slice up the fish and serve it.

1350
01:03:50,181 --> 01:03:51,181
(Similar to Japanese amberjack, it's in the carangidae family.)

1351
01:03:51,182 --> 01:03:52,721
They are caught in large numbers,

1352
01:03:53,121 --> 01:03:55,821
so the price is very low now.

1353
01:03:56,321 --> 01:03:59,191
(It inhabits the warm waters of the Jeju region.)

1354
01:03:59,791 --> 01:04:02,290
Consumers would probably be shocked to hear this,

1355
01:04:02,291 --> 01:04:04,030
but the price is incredibly cheap.

1356
01:04:04,031 --> 01:04:07,031
(The overwhelming cost advantage of a business on Jeju Island)

1357
01:04:07,231 --> 01:04:09,071
We thought about all that before starting this, of course.

1358
01:04:09,401 --> 01:04:10,631
Without the option,

1359
01:04:10,901 --> 01:04:11,930
a budget of 300 dollars would be impossible.

1360
01:04:11,931 --> 01:04:13,001
It'd easily cost 1,000 dollars.

1361
01:04:13,141 --> 01:04:15,271
Jun Seong, the important thing is that we're in Chungnam Province now.

1362
01:04:16,271 --> 01:04:17,710
- This is Chungnam Province, right?
- Yes.

1363
01:04:17,711 --> 01:04:19,711
You know what it is famous for here. It's kalguksu.

1364
01:04:20,211 --> 01:04:22,350
(The region with the highest number of kalguksu restaurants per capita)

1365
01:04:22,351 --> 01:04:26,151
Apparently, people here have a huge preference for noodle dishes.

1366
01:04:27,281 --> 01:04:30,351
I have absolute confidence when it comes to noodle dishes.

1367
01:04:32,821 --> 01:04:34,791
We will serve Jeju-style raw fish guksu.

1368
01:04:37,431 --> 01:04:39,260
And it would be a bit disappointing just to have noodles.

1369
01:04:39,261 --> 01:04:41,061
So I prepared pork suyuk.

1370
01:04:42,601 --> 01:04:45,541
And it will be served with laver that I roast myself.

1371
01:04:46,501 --> 01:04:48,500
You might not know it, but eating noodles...

1372
01:04:48,501 --> 01:04:50,371
wrapped in laver is incredibly good.

1373
01:04:51,941 --> 01:04:55,581
(Roasted laver to accompany the noodles)

1374
01:04:57,181 --> 01:04:58,511
Add the bean sprouts, Jun Seong.

1375
01:04:59,481 --> 01:05:02,051
It's a set meal. I like serving a set meal.

1376
01:05:02,521 --> 01:05:04,820
It feels a bit lacking if there's only a single menu item.

1377
01:05:04,821 --> 01:05:06,890
(Jeju raw fish guksu set: 17.9 dollars)

1378
01:05:06,891 --> 01:05:08,390
And Jun Seong knows a recipe...

1379
01:05:08,391 --> 01:05:11,161
that can make marinated shrimp within ten minutes.

1380
01:05:11,331 --> 01:05:12,401
Is that right? Is it ten minutes?

1381
01:05:12,801 --> 01:05:14,101
It's a bit pressuring when you put it that way.

1382
01:05:16,531 --> 01:05:18,570
When we have...

1383
01:05:18,571 --> 01:05:21,201
leftover shrimp at our restaurant...

1384
01:05:21,301 --> 01:05:23,940
and want to eat it for lunch, we can't marinate it right away.

1385
01:05:23,941 --> 01:05:26,811
And we have a vacuum sealer at our restaurant.

1386
01:05:27,141 --> 01:05:29,451
If you use it to suck the air out,

1387
01:05:29,681 --> 01:05:32,011
the shrimp gets marinated in just five minutes.

1388
01:05:33,821 --> 01:05:36,021
But we couldn't bring the commercial vacuum sealer here.

1389
01:05:36,291 --> 01:05:37,820
So we decided to use...

1390
01:05:37,821 --> 01:05:39,991
a vacuum airtight container sold at a dollar shop.

1391
01:05:40,491 --> 01:05:42,631
(A vacuum airtight container)

1392
01:05:45,461 --> 01:05:49,501
The sauce is forced into the shrimp without any separate aging time,

1393
01:05:49,831 --> 01:05:51,900
so the texture of shrimp doesn't break down from aging.

1394
01:05:51,901 --> 01:05:54,770
- That's true. It's not mushy.
- It just absorbs the flavor...

1395
01:05:54,771 --> 01:05:56,211
while keeping the firm texture.

1396
01:05:57,171 --> 01:05:59,181
(Gotgan)

1397
01:06:01,781 --> 01:06:04,711
I make good perilla oil guksu. For the clean taste.

1398
01:06:05,981 --> 01:06:09,190
So we prepared perilla oil guksu with marinated shrimp.

1399
01:06:09,191 --> 01:06:10,391
(Jeju marinated shrimp guksu set: 17.9 dollars)

1400
01:06:13,691 --> 01:06:16,161
There is one hour left before the business starts.

1401
01:06:17,491 --> 01:06:21,131
(The participants must decorate the exterior themselves.)

1402
01:06:22,431 --> 01:06:25,771
(There's one restaurant that catches everyone's eye.)

1403
01:06:26,241 --> 01:06:29,371
He really knows how to utilize props. He's so good.

1404
01:06:30,111 --> 01:06:33,681
Chef Kim Hoon is amazing at designing the exterior.

1405
01:06:34,581 --> 01:06:37,251
(The LA food truck concept)

1406
01:06:37,381 --> 01:06:39,881
He is someone who can lead the trend.

1407
01:06:40,221 --> 01:06:43,221
He is extremely talented and has great ideas.

1408
01:06:43,491 --> 01:06:45,960
When it comes to running a business, Chef Kim Hoon is the best.

1409
01:06:45,961 --> 01:06:49,491
He is someone who caters perfectly to modern tastes.

1410
01:06:50,061 --> 01:06:53,000
Hello, I'm Chef Kim Hoon who is running restaurants...

1411
01:06:53,001 --> 01:06:54,161
in Yongridan-gil.

1412
01:06:54,601 --> 01:06:57,270
I run Sam Sam Sam, an American-style comfort food restaurant,

1413
01:06:57,271 --> 01:07:01,041
Teddy Beurre House, and Namdo Dwaejichon.

1414
01:07:01,741 --> 01:07:04,540
The genre I'm handling has now become...

1415
01:07:04,541 --> 01:07:06,341
a hot spot brand that targets Gen Z.

1416
01:07:06,511 --> 01:07:10,111
In this specific genre, I believe I have the strongest momentum now.

1417
01:07:11,351 --> 01:07:13,081
I honestly wonder, "Who here is actually better..."

1418
01:07:13,381 --> 01:07:15,381
"at business than I am?"

1419
01:07:16,421 --> 01:07:18,320
There aren't many people who have actually run businesses...

1420
01:07:18,321 --> 01:07:20,821
in many different commercial districts.

1421
01:07:22,831 --> 01:07:23,931
But I do have that experience.

1422
01:07:24,591 --> 01:07:26,500
I've been in office districts like Yeouido and Gwanghwamun,

1423
01:07:26,501 --> 01:07:29,231
and I've even done it in specialized commercial zones and food courts.

1424
01:07:29,901 --> 01:07:33,941
I think this could be my stage.

1425
01:07:35,601 --> 01:07:36,941
How many kilograms of meat do we have?

1426
01:07:37,071 --> 01:07:38,211
We have 16kg.

1427
01:07:39,311 --> 01:07:41,781
- I'll marinate the beef first.
- Okay.

1428
01:07:42,681 --> 01:07:44,881
The menu item we prepared is...

1429
01:07:46,451 --> 01:07:48,820
tenderloin steak rice, loaded with tenderloin.

1430
01:07:48,821 --> 01:07:50,090
(Tenderloin steak rice: 13 dollars)

1431
01:07:50,091 --> 01:07:51,951
Office districts are areas...

1432
01:07:52,091 --> 01:07:54,190
where a high volume of repeat purchases occurs.

1433
01:07:54,191 --> 01:07:56,131
I currently run restaurants in office districts...

1434
01:07:56,831 --> 01:07:58,531
like Gwanghwamun, Yeouido, and Jamsil.

1435
01:07:59,031 --> 01:08:01,900
Since those areas trap customers like a pot,

1436
01:08:01,901 --> 01:08:05,130
the same office workers end up eating the same things repeatedly.

1437
01:08:05,131 --> 01:08:08,641
So the food which can be eaten in daily life is successful there.

1438
01:08:08,701 --> 01:08:09,840
(Budae jjigae, spicy stir-fried pork rice)

1439
01:08:09,841 --> 01:08:11,041
(Homemade tonkatsu)

1440
01:08:11,611 --> 01:08:15,411
However, this is a restaurant that only operates for a single day.

1441
01:08:15,641 --> 01:08:18,380
Still, we should make this place a hot spot.

1442
01:08:18,381 --> 01:08:21,221
It could be a big event for the office workers here.

1443
01:08:21,421 --> 01:08:23,790
Since we have to take both factors into account,

1444
01:08:23,791 --> 01:08:26,721
we can't simply judge this place as a typical office district.

1445
01:08:27,121 --> 01:08:28,190
So I thought about a place that targets office workers...

1446
01:08:28,191 --> 01:08:30,060
but is still considered trendy.

1447
01:08:30,061 --> 01:08:31,731
There is actually one such place in Korea.

1448
01:08:32,561 --> 01:08:33,730
It's The Hyundai Seoul in Yeouido.

1449
01:08:33,731 --> 01:08:35,230
(A specialized commercial area...)

1450
01:08:35,231 --> 01:08:36,771
(where an office district and hot spots coexist)

1451
01:08:37,001 --> 01:08:39,071
I believe data never lies.

1452
01:08:39,441 --> 01:08:42,240
If we move according to that data, we won't get eliminated.

1453
01:08:42,241 --> 01:08:44,971
That's how we will survive. I have total confidence in that.

1454
01:08:45,741 --> 01:08:47,840
It's an office district, but we're not just targeting office workers.

1455
01:08:47,841 --> 01:08:50,050
We need to do something trendy, but it shouldn't be too trendy...

1456
01:08:50,051 --> 01:08:51,351
because there are many office workers.

1457
01:08:51,881 --> 01:08:53,480
Let's just make it simple.

1458
01:08:53,481 --> 01:08:54,821
What's the number one item in sales at The Hyundai Seoul?

1459
01:08:54,921 --> 01:08:57,121
Once we find out what it is, it's game over.

1460
01:08:57,851 --> 01:08:59,461
We did some research.

1461
01:08:59,491 --> 01:09:00,860
When I looked into the best-selling items...

1462
01:09:00,861 --> 01:09:03,791
during lunchtime at places like department stores,

1463
01:09:03,931 --> 01:09:06,201
it turned out to be the steak rice. So I chose it.

1464
01:09:07,931 --> 01:09:11,330
If you can have a hearty steak rice for 13 dollars during lunchtime,

1465
01:09:11,331 --> 01:09:13,601
you will absolutely buy it. I'd even eat it five times a week.

1466
01:09:14,771 --> 01:09:16,910
What is the menu item that you think will do the best?

1467
01:09:16,911 --> 01:09:18,371
The steak rice.

1468
01:09:18,811 --> 01:09:20,310
I think the steak rice is selling well.

1469
01:09:20,311 --> 01:09:21,910
They're ordering the tenderloin steak rice.

1470
01:09:21,911 --> 01:09:23,711
I knew it would be popular.

1471
01:09:24,611 --> 01:09:27,080
First of all, a meat rice bowl is one of those items that never fails.

1472
01:09:27,081 --> 01:09:28,951
And on top of that, it's a steak.

1473
01:09:29,891 --> 01:09:31,520
Beef tenderloin? They're using beef tenderloin?

1474
01:09:31,521 --> 01:09:33,191
That means they're not going to skimp on costs.

1475
01:09:33,891 --> 01:09:35,590
(Tenderloin steak rice, Ingredient cost: 572.46 dollars)

1476
01:09:35,591 --> 01:09:36,991
It's 572 dollars!

1477
01:09:38,161 --> 01:09:41,861
(The number 1 restaurant in negative ingredient cost)

1478
01:09:42,031 --> 01:09:43,301
This is all about momentum.

1479
01:09:43,931 --> 01:09:45,940
I thought that if we embrace the negative budget...

1480
01:09:45,941 --> 01:09:49,171
and serve a generous amount of meat as a steak rice,

1481
01:09:49,471 --> 01:09:52,141
it would show our sincerity to the customers.

1482
01:09:53,081 --> 01:09:54,740
The fact that you can have...

1483
01:09:54,741 --> 01:09:57,911
a tenderloin steak rice for just 13 dollars is a huge merit.

1484
01:09:58,251 --> 01:10:01,050
If you pay just 0.1 dollars more than our hamburger steak,

1485
01:10:01,051 --> 01:10:02,351
you can eat real beef.

1486
01:10:02,521 --> 01:10:06,261
(Black bean rice with hamburger steak: 12.9 dollars)

1487
01:10:06,491 --> 01:10:08,391
You get a whole chunk of beef.

1488
01:10:08,661 --> 01:10:10,331
I thought it would be tough.

1489
01:10:10,791 --> 01:10:13,061
The person I'm keeping an eye on...

1490
01:10:13,761 --> 01:10:14,861
is Kwak Dong Hoon.

1491
01:10:15,971 --> 01:10:18,301
While Seoul has Kim Hoon, Busan has Kwak Dong Hoon.

1492
01:10:19,541 --> 01:10:21,041
I thought it would be fun.

1493
01:10:22,271 --> 01:10:25,011
I have a desire for people to notice me.

1494
01:10:25,941 --> 01:10:29,550
Since we've often sold over 1,000 dollars per hour,

1495
01:10:29,551 --> 01:10:33,081
I think we can finish it within lunchtime for sure.

1496
01:10:33,681 --> 01:10:36,221
(Number One)

1497
01:10:36,291 --> 01:10:37,491
Let's have confidence.

1498
01:10:38,591 --> 01:10:41,121
We have our years of hard-earned experience.

1499
01:10:41,961 --> 01:10:45,630
I think the government institutions probably have their own cafeterias.

1500
01:10:45,631 --> 01:10:48,001
We can't sell something that you would find in a cafeteria.

1501
01:10:48,931 --> 01:10:51,601
Wouldn't they want to try something new and trendy?

1502
01:10:52,741 --> 01:10:56,041
The other chefs tend to do what they are best at.

1503
01:10:56,541 --> 01:10:58,771
French cuisine, no question asked.

1504
01:10:59,011 --> 01:11:01,810
I think it's better to include jjamppong on the menu.

1505
01:11:01,811 --> 01:11:03,610
We're chefs, so the food has to be good.

1506
01:11:03,611 --> 01:11:04,611
Of course, it has to be good.

1507
01:11:04,612 --> 01:11:08,121
They seem to be serving the food that they can make best,

1508
01:11:08,621 --> 01:11:11,491
but I look at the customers' needs.

1509
01:11:12,491 --> 01:11:13,991
What customers want to eat.

1510
01:11:14,721 --> 01:11:19,501
We are the type who make food that consumers desire.

1511
01:11:20,201 --> 01:11:25,431
That's why I'm planning to set up what is needed in Gwangalli.

1512
01:11:26,101 --> 01:11:29,671
I think it's best to make food that doesn't exist in Sejong.

1513
01:11:30,671 --> 01:11:32,010
That is my strategy.

1514
01:11:32,011 --> 01:11:33,211
(The needs hunter)

1515
01:11:33,841 --> 01:11:35,311
What we are making is...

1516
01:11:36,081 --> 01:11:38,380
chimichanga, which is our specialty.

1517
01:11:38,381 --> 01:11:39,420
(Jumbo chimichanga: 12.8 dollars)

1518
01:11:39,421 --> 01:11:40,750
And a chili cheese stick.

1519
01:11:40,751 --> 01:11:41,981
(Chili cheese stick: 6.8 dollars)

1520
01:11:42,081 --> 01:11:45,521
These are the items that are trending on social media now.

1521
01:11:45,851 --> 01:11:47,620
The jumbo chimichanga is a dish...

1522
01:11:47,621 --> 01:11:50,431
that went viral on social media...

1523
01:11:50,691 --> 01:11:53,460
and created explosive waiting lines.

1524
01:11:53,461 --> 01:11:55,501
That's how I'd describe the item.

1525
01:11:55,631 --> 01:11:59,571
Earlier, some of the participants looked at our menu...

1526
01:12:00,141 --> 01:12:01,671
and asked what a chimichanga was.

1527
01:12:03,141 --> 01:12:06,281
Jumbo chimichanga and chili cheese stick combo.

1528
01:12:06,541 --> 01:12:07,911
What is chimichanga?

1529
01:12:08,511 --> 01:12:09,751
What is chimichanga?

1530
01:12:10,181 --> 01:12:13,151
Is it something like dim sum?

1531
01:12:13,921 --> 01:12:15,650
That means there are people who don't know it.

1532
01:12:15,651 --> 01:12:17,451
Wouldn't it be even more so in Sejong?

1533
01:12:18,691 --> 01:12:22,660
A chimichanga is a dish made of a deep-fried burrito...

1534
01:12:22,661 --> 01:12:25,231
generously covered with sauce.

1535
01:12:26,261 --> 01:12:29,631
First, we prepared the fillings that go inside the chimichanga.

1536
01:12:30,201 --> 01:12:31,571
We cooked rice...

1537
01:12:31,901 --> 01:12:33,941
to mix it with Mexican sauce.

1538
01:12:38,441 --> 01:12:41,681
This is the exact moment where my experience...

1539
01:12:42,411 --> 01:12:46,221
as a military cook shines through.

1540
01:12:48,581 --> 01:12:51,091
(Mexican sauce rice, the base of chimichanga's taste)

1541
01:12:51,151 --> 01:12:53,090
Then we stir-fried and seasoned...

1542
01:12:53,091 --> 01:12:55,191
chicken and pork.

1543
01:12:55,291 --> 01:12:57,360
We also deep-fried french fries.

1544
01:12:57,361 --> 01:12:59,761
(Fries to add the crispy texture)

1545
01:13:00,131 --> 01:13:03,571
(Chicken sauce, pork sauce, fries)

1546
01:13:03,801 --> 01:13:06,901
I made unique pickles using the red onions.

1547
01:13:07,141 --> 01:13:09,971
That evens out the greasiness of the chimichanga.

1548
01:13:11,041 --> 01:13:13,541
As much as we're proud of this dish,

1549
01:13:13,941 --> 01:13:16,051
we're desperate to present it.

1550
01:13:17,951 --> 01:13:18,951
It's delicious.

1551
01:13:22,451 --> 01:13:25,721
The current time is 10:50am.

1552
01:13:26,291 --> 01:13:28,591
Ten minutes before the business begins.

1553
01:13:29,831 --> 01:13:31,331
Oh, I'm tight on schedule.

1554
01:13:32,331 --> 01:13:33,931
I'm pressed for time more than I thought.

1555
01:13:45,941 --> 01:13:47,041
Okay. Done.

1556
01:13:51,681 --> 01:13:52,880
(Gyeol, BokBok, Gotgan)

1557
01:13:52,881 --> 01:13:53,980
Round One.

1558
01:13:53,981 --> 01:13:56,921
A 1,000 dollar sales race begins.

1559
01:13:58,491 --> 01:14:00,861
The blinds will come down now.

1560
01:14:02,731 --> 01:14:05,631
(Out of 20 restaurants here,)

1561
01:14:06,931 --> 01:14:09,501
(2 will close.)

1562
01:14:09,831 --> 01:14:11,371
- We'll now begin.
- Oh, no.

1563
01:14:13,841 --> 01:14:15,471
- It's starting.
- I'm nervous.

1564
01:14:15,711 --> 01:14:16,741
Here we go.

1565
01:14:19,581 --> 01:14:22,781
No matter how many restaurants I opened before,

1566
01:14:23,111 --> 01:14:25,381
it's always nervous to open a new one.

1567
01:14:25,881 --> 01:14:28,121
Will people choose my restaurant?

1568
01:14:28,651 --> 01:14:29,821
Will they be happy with it?

1569
01:14:30,151 --> 01:14:31,791
It's time for the cold evaluation.

1570
01:14:32,721 --> 01:14:33,991
- One, two, three, go.
- Go.

1571
01:14:34,461 --> 01:14:36,691
It was pretty tense.

1572
01:14:37,061 --> 01:14:38,131
Good luck.

1573
01:14:39,331 --> 01:14:40,401
- We can do it.
- We can do it.

1574
01:14:42,271 --> 01:14:46,441
(Government Complex Sejong)

1575
01:14:55,651 --> 01:14:57,881
(Government Complex Sejong)

1576
01:14:58,251 --> 01:15:01,320
(Time to open a new restaurant regardless of their titles)

1577
01:15:01,321 --> 01:15:04,491
The Street Arena door opens.

1578
01:15:08,861 --> 01:15:09,960
- Cool.
- Can we go?

1579
01:15:09,961 --> 01:15:11,560
(The mics are worn on only those who want to.)

1580
01:15:11,561 --> 01:15:13,301
- There are so many.
- It's crazy.

1581
01:15:14,761 --> 01:15:16,631
It's pretty. There are so many restaurants.

1582
01:15:17,231 --> 01:15:19,201
How are we going to order everything here?

1583
01:15:20,341 --> 01:15:21,740
Where do you want to go first?

1584
01:15:21,741 --> 01:15:23,211
- Check it out.
- What do you want to eat?

1585
01:15:24,211 --> 01:15:25,541
- It's opening.
- People are coming.

1586
01:15:26,611 --> 01:15:28,581
I wonder what the first customer is getting.

1587
01:15:30,881 --> 01:15:33,251
(Get out of my way.)

1588
01:15:33,851 --> 01:15:36,090
- It's going to get crowded.
- Something smells delicious.

1589
01:15:36,091 --> 01:15:37,150
(The customers scatter toward the restaurants.)

1590
01:15:37,151 --> 01:15:38,221
Handmade ice cream?

1591
01:15:38,751 --> 01:15:39,761
Then...

1592
01:15:41,161 --> 01:15:43,331
The customers are here. Hey, they're here.

1593
01:15:43,691 --> 01:15:45,561
They're coming this way.

1594
01:15:46,001 --> 01:15:48,031
Hey, Hoon. They're coming. They're coming this way.

1595
01:15:48,501 --> 01:15:50,531
They're looking at us. They're coming.

1596
01:15:51,431 --> 01:15:53,401
- But the food...
- Everything sounds delicious.

1597
01:15:53,871 --> 01:15:55,471
There's so much to choose from.

1598
01:15:55,971 --> 01:15:57,971
I've always wanted to try that. The chili cheese stick.

1599
01:15:58,341 --> 01:15:59,740
- That's trendy now.
- What?

1600
01:15:59,741 --> 01:16:00,941
- The chili cheese stick.
- Really?

1601
01:16:01,041 --> 01:16:04,251
(Immediately reacting to Kwak Dong Hoon's trendy item)

1602
01:16:05,151 --> 01:16:06,180
Sunlin.

1603
01:16:06,181 --> 01:16:08,021
I want to eat everything. There are also dumplings.

1604
01:16:08,451 --> 01:16:09,551
- Do you want to go around first?
- Yes.

1605
01:16:09,891 --> 01:16:11,220
- Wolfie's?
- That sounds delicious.

1606
01:16:11,221 --> 01:16:12,521
Black bean rice.

1607
01:16:13,061 --> 01:16:14,161
Hamburger steak.

1608
01:16:16,431 --> 01:16:17,991
They went halfway around.

1609
01:16:18,961 --> 01:16:20,261
Did they linger and leave?

1610
01:16:20,431 --> 01:16:22,301
Yes. I think they're checking out all the items.

1611
01:16:23,101 --> 01:16:25,300
When the customers come, they'll go around at least once...

1612
01:16:25,301 --> 01:16:26,941
before choosing the food.

1613
01:16:27,171 --> 01:16:33,811
(The customer's route)

1614
01:16:34,111 --> 01:16:35,611
After going around,

1615
01:16:35,851 --> 01:16:37,311
where would they go first?

1616
01:16:37,651 --> 01:16:38,651
Let's go.

1617
01:16:38,911 --> 01:16:41,220
There's something I want to try. Is there raw fish?

1618
01:16:41,221 --> 01:16:42,951
- Let's go around then.
- Sure.

1619
01:16:43,091 --> 01:16:44,091
(Vermicelli tteokbokki, spring cabbage bibimbap)

1620
01:16:44,092 --> 01:16:45,221
Oh, tteokbokki.

1621
01:16:45,591 --> 01:16:47,691
Spring cabbage is really popular these days.

1622
01:16:48,961 --> 01:16:50,061
Oh, curry.

1623
01:16:50,461 --> 01:16:51,491
Karaage.

1624
01:16:52,291 --> 01:16:53,431
That looks delicious too.

1625
01:16:53,461 --> 01:16:55,200
(Passing for now)

1626
01:16:55,201 --> 01:16:56,231
Puffer fish soup.

1627
01:16:56,731 --> 01:16:58,531
- Mianbao xia.
- Mianbao xia.

1628
01:17:00,241 --> 01:17:01,300
I want to eat it all.

1629
01:17:01,301 --> 01:17:02,571
Oh, marinated shrimp.

1630
01:17:03,371 --> 01:17:05,241
- We can't see the chefs?
- Nice.

1631
01:17:05,371 --> 01:17:06,381
What?

1632
01:17:06,841 --> 01:17:08,481
There's also glutinous rice nurungji.

1633
01:17:10,051 --> 01:17:11,511
- I'm having that for now.
- What?

1634
01:17:11,781 --> 01:17:13,321
- I want to eat that.
- Go get it.

1635
01:17:15,451 --> 01:17:20,061
(What does the first customer choose?)

1636
01:17:23,331 --> 01:17:24,390
Mom.

1637
01:17:24,391 --> 01:17:25,800
(Gotgan)

1638
01:17:25,801 --> 01:17:27,831
- No customers?
- They're ordering.

1639
01:17:29,271 --> 01:17:30,570
- We order here.
- Marinated shrimp.

1640
01:17:30,571 --> 01:17:32,741
(Jeju marinated shrimp noodle combo for 17.90 dollars)

1641
01:17:33,601 --> 01:17:34,900
One marinated shrimp.

1642
01:17:34,901 --> 01:17:36,211
(The first order goes to Kim Mi Ryeong.)

1643
01:17:37,111 --> 01:17:38,541
Office workers want to eat quickly...

1644
01:17:38,671 --> 01:17:40,640
and get some rest during lunch.

1645
01:17:40,641 --> 01:17:42,650
I prepared everything, so I could serve it right away.

1646
01:17:42,651 --> 01:17:44,181
(1. Vegetables and sauce prepared)

1647
01:17:44,811 --> 01:17:46,881
(2. Roasted laver prepared)

1648
01:17:47,481 --> 01:17:50,020
(3. Boil noodles and rinse them in cold water.)

1649
01:17:50,021 --> 01:17:51,150
I'll prepare the cutting board.

1650
01:17:51,151 --> 01:17:52,590
- Just rinse the noodles for me.
- Okay.

1651
01:17:52,591 --> 01:17:53,691
(Everything is prepared in advance to reduce the wait time.)

1652
01:17:54,321 --> 01:17:55,991
(When the order comes in,)

1653
01:17:56,691 --> 01:18:00,761
(it's quickly prepared for office workers.)

1654
01:18:05,701 --> 01:18:06,841
I need more black pepper.

1655
01:18:07,301 --> 01:18:08,301
- Is this okay?
- Yes.

1656
01:18:08,302 --> 01:18:09,310
Let's go.

1657
01:18:09,311 --> 01:18:11,610
(It took a minute and half to be served.)

1658
01:18:11,611 --> 01:18:13,210
(Exclaiming)

1659
01:18:13,211 --> 01:18:14,381
For the first round,

1660
01:18:14,781 --> 01:18:17,150
we decided to sell everything quickly during lunch.

1661
01:18:17,151 --> 01:18:19,051
We plan to rest during dinner.

1662
01:18:19,281 --> 01:18:20,281
Yes.

1663
01:18:20,921 --> 01:18:22,820
(Gotgan plans to emphasize on the speed.)

1664
01:18:22,821 --> 01:18:24,191
One is ready.

1665
01:18:26,561 --> 01:18:28,961
Why do we need to talk when we're here to work?

1666
01:18:29,161 --> 01:18:30,561
Everything is prepared in order.

1667
01:18:31,831 --> 01:18:33,231
Thank you. Enjoy.

1668
01:18:35,871 --> 01:18:37,571
I think we have to order a lot.

1669
01:18:38,501 --> 01:18:40,601
(Jeju marinated shrimp noodle combo for 17.90 dollars)

1670
01:18:44,441 --> 01:18:47,010
When I was first told about the mission,

1671
01:18:47,011 --> 01:18:48,111
I was told it'd be a blind test.

1672
01:18:48,311 --> 01:18:50,151
And that we couldn't talk to the customers that much.

1673
01:18:50,511 --> 01:18:51,980
If we can't explain the dish,

1674
01:18:51,981 --> 01:18:53,050
and if it's a blind test,

1675
01:18:53,051 --> 01:18:55,481
we might as well write it nicely and serve it with the food.

1676
01:18:56,091 --> 01:18:58,390
So, tips like...

1677
01:18:58,391 --> 01:18:59,720
how it tastes better with laver.

1678
01:18:59,721 --> 01:19:01,221
We wrote those tips on paper.

1679
01:19:03,531 --> 01:19:04,891
We should try it with laver.

1680
01:19:05,131 --> 01:19:06,131
- Really?
- Yes.

1681
01:19:06,132 --> 01:19:07,501
It's written here.

1682
01:19:08,701 --> 01:19:11,101
Wrap the raw fish and noodles with laver.

1683
01:19:18,271 --> 01:19:24,151
(The customers try the food as Gotgan intends.)

1684
01:19:24,781 --> 01:19:27,050
It's the best bibim guksu I've ever had.

1685
01:19:27,051 --> 01:19:28,721
- I know. I agree.
- So good.

1686
01:19:30,121 --> 01:19:31,651
How come we're not getting any orders?

1687
01:19:32,821 --> 01:19:34,091
No one...

1688
01:19:35,161 --> 01:19:36,691
- Ramyeon sounds good.
- That looks good.

1689
01:19:36,791 --> 01:19:38,291
- Let's get ramyeon too.
- Yes.

1690
01:19:38,691 --> 01:19:40,001
We saw everything.

1691
01:19:40,401 --> 01:19:41,601
What should we eat?

1692
01:19:41,961 --> 01:19:43,531
Gosh. What should we get first?

1693
01:19:44,471 --> 01:19:45,601
Do you want to check it out again?

1694
01:19:46,041 --> 01:19:48,100
- Oh, it's steak rice.
- Oh, steak rice sounds good.

1695
01:19:48,101 --> 01:19:49,311
I want to have steak rice.

1696
01:19:53,281 --> 01:19:54,741
Oh, what? This is crazy.

1697
01:19:54,841 --> 01:19:55,911
Is it two?

1698
01:19:56,511 --> 01:19:57,551
- Two?
- One?

1699
01:19:57,781 --> 01:19:59,381
- One. Oh, it's one.
- One.

1700
01:19:59,781 --> 01:20:02,620
(Immediately followed by more customers)

1701
01:20:02,621 --> 01:20:03,751
Okay. We're getting more.

1702
01:20:04,121 --> 01:20:05,291
Two steak rice.

1703
01:20:06,091 --> 01:20:07,761
What? Why are you getting so many?

1704
01:20:08,591 --> 01:20:09,991
Let's go. Oh, hot.

1705
01:20:10,291 --> 01:20:11,591
See you later.

1706
01:20:11,991 --> 01:20:13,201
See you up there.

1707
01:20:15,031 --> 01:20:17,201
I should roast the meat, right?

1708
01:20:22,271 --> 01:20:23,411
Place onions.

1709
01:20:24,311 --> 01:20:25,470
Add the tare sauce.

1710
01:20:25,471 --> 01:20:27,711
(Stir-fried onion on a bowl of rice, tare sauce)

1711
01:20:27,981 --> 01:20:29,481
- The meat is ready.
- Okay.

1712
01:20:32,251 --> 01:20:33,421
For one serving, right?

1713
01:20:34,021 --> 01:20:35,021
Is it a little too much?

1714
01:20:35,451 --> 01:20:36,521
It's a little too much, but it's good.

1715
01:20:37,321 --> 01:20:38,490
Since it's for our first customer.

1716
01:20:38,491 --> 01:20:40,961
(Tenderloin steak rice for 13 dollars)

1717
01:20:41,421 --> 01:20:42,830
You can take this.

1718
01:20:42,831 --> 01:20:43,931
Enjoy.

1719
01:20:44,691 --> 01:20:46,431
- Enjoy. Thank you.
- Thank you.

1720
01:20:47,161 --> 01:20:48,500
- Thank you for the food.
- Hurry up and try it.

1721
01:20:48,501 --> 01:20:49,501
Okay.

1722
01:20:54,771 --> 01:20:56,110
(Exclaiming)

1723
01:20:56,111 --> 01:20:57,311
- Good?
- Yes.

1724
01:20:57,871 --> 01:20:59,440
The steak is really good.

1725
01:20:59,441 --> 01:21:00,710
Yes. They did a good job of grilling.

1726
01:21:00,711 --> 01:21:02,141
It's not chewy at all.

1727
01:21:02,411 --> 01:21:04,581
This meat is different. I can't stop eating it.

1728
01:21:05,581 --> 01:21:07,281
- I know. It's not dry at all.
- No.

1729
01:21:07,651 --> 01:21:09,891
- I'd totally pay for this price.
- Me too.

1730
01:21:10,751 --> 01:21:12,651
If we could get it for this price in Sejong,

1731
01:21:12,991 --> 01:21:14,321
- we'd totally line up for it.
- Yes.

1732
01:21:15,621 --> 01:21:18,031
- They're checking it out first.
- Did they go to the next door?

1733
01:21:18,491 --> 01:21:19,830
Come on. Come to this side.

1734
01:21:19,831 --> 01:21:21,331
How come no one's coming to this side?

1735
01:21:21,731 --> 01:21:24,201
- They're here.
- They're here.

1736
01:21:25,101 --> 01:21:28,541
(Gyeol, BokBok, Gotgan)

1737
01:21:28,841 --> 01:21:31,071
- They left.
- Did they leave?

1738
01:21:32,981 --> 01:21:36,051
I was begging for them to stop, but they kept leaving.

1739
01:21:36,211 --> 01:21:40,081
It's been a while since I waited for customers to come.

1740
01:21:40,281 --> 01:21:42,451
It's the first time...

1741
01:21:42,551 --> 01:21:44,790
I've ever waited for customers to come this desperately.

1742
01:21:44,791 --> 01:21:45,821
Gosh.

1743
01:21:46,821 --> 01:21:47,821
Gosh.

1744
01:21:48,091 --> 01:21:50,660
There's no room to eat in Mokran.

1745
01:21:50,661 --> 01:21:52,061
Try it here.

1746
01:21:52,231 --> 01:21:53,231
That's what I mean.

1747
01:21:54,231 --> 01:21:57,001
(Tiptoeing desperately)

1748
01:21:59,131 --> 01:22:00,201
Well...

1749
01:22:00,871 --> 01:22:02,171
We have one person coming.

1750
01:22:04,911 --> 01:22:06,641
I think she's ordering.

1751
01:22:10,281 --> 01:22:11,351
We got it.

1752
01:22:12,451 --> 01:22:14,121
- What is it?
- One jjamppong.

1753
01:22:14,451 --> 01:22:15,821
One best mianbao xia.

1754
01:22:16,921 --> 01:22:18,721
One mianbao xia, one jjamppong.

1755
01:22:19,561 --> 01:22:20,761
I'll make it delicious.

1756
01:22:27,301 --> 01:22:29,531
I can't stop laughing even making jjamppong.

1757
01:22:29,901 --> 01:22:31,570
I can't believe how happy I am...

1758
01:22:31,571 --> 01:22:32,871
to get an order of 1 jjamppong and 1 mianbao xia.

1759
01:22:34,001 --> 01:22:35,340
In my restaurant...

1760
01:22:35,341 --> 01:22:37,441
(Laughing)

1761
01:22:37,741 --> 01:22:40,740
If we make it look delicious, other people will see it and go,

1762
01:22:40,741 --> 01:22:42,081
"Where did you get that from?"

1763
01:22:42,241 --> 01:22:43,481
"Where's that from?"

1764
01:22:44,811 --> 01:22:46,180
(Current sales: 27 dollars)

1765
01:22:46,181 --> 01:22:47,221
Done.

1766
01:22:48,751 --> 01:22:51,621
(Another restaurant at the same time)

1767
01:22:54,391 --> 01:22:55,521
It's the spring cabbage.

1768
01:22:55,891 --> 01:22:57,791
(Turning away)

1769
01:22:58,191 --> 01:23:02,130
(Customers keep passing.)

1770
01:23:02,131 --> 01:23:03,431
(Arirang House)

1771
01:23:03,771 --> 01:23:05,271
It seems...

1772
01:23:05,631 --> 01:23:07,401
there's no rush.

1773
01:23:08,271 --> 01:23:09,741
Is everyone else the same?

1774
01:23:10,511 --> 01:23:12,471
It's hard to sell 1,000 dollars during lunch.

1775
01:23:13,211 --> 01:23:15,611
We have to work to death to make that happen.

1776
01:23:16,481 --> 01:23:17,610
Business is tough.

1777
01:23:17,611 --> 01:23:19,051
(Go Min Seong, teammate)

1778
01:23:19,681 --> 01:23:22,120
Let's face it. Office workers...

1779
01:23:22,121 --> 01:23:24,891
don't grab something fancy for lunch.

1780
01:23:25,191 --> 01:23:27,521
So I picked the menu you'd find easily.

1781
01:23:28,221 --> 01:23:30,890
The bibimbap with spring cabbage and cockle...

1782
01:23:30,891 --> 01:23:32,561
and bossam combo.

1783
01:23:33,231 --> 01:23:35,960
We need to sell something appropriate for the business area.

1784
01:23:35,961 --> 01:23:38,830
So I thought a lot about...

1785
01:23:38,831 --> 01:23:41,100
what they'd want for lunch.

1786
01:23:41,101 --> 01:23:42,200
It's mostly men.

1787
01:23:42,201 --> 01:23:44,711
There are women, but a lot more men.

1788
01:23:45,641 --> 01:23:48,610
(There are more men than women.)

1789
01:23:48,611 --> 01:23:50,511
And they don't like to share.

1790
01:23:52,611 --> 01:23:55,681
(They don't share the food.)

1791
01:23:55,951 --> 01:23:58,790
I thought they'd have...

1792
01:23:58,791 --> 01:24:01,161
soup in the end.

1793
01:24:01,561 --> 01:24:03,131
Something that can be boiled and served right away.

1794
01:24:03,291 --> 01:24:04,831
